 {"id":"bd-fu67","title":"Investigate br mixed-prefix rebuild and doctor false-corruption on repaired beads DB","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-03-12T17:15:34.935933634Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-12T17:27:11.768459850Z","closed_at":"2026-03-12T17:27:11.755129565Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"comments":[{"id":102,"issue_id":"bd-fu67","author":"Ubuntu","text":"Investigation Results:

1. The "database disk image is malformed" error reported by `br doctor` is caused by actual SQLite index corruption (`idx_issues_assignee`) in the local `.beads/beads.db`.
2. Running `br doctor --repair` fails because the JSONL file contains multiple prefixes (the old `process_triage-` prefix and the new `bd-` prefix set in `.beads/config.yaml`). The internal repair process invokes `br sync` but doesn't pass `--force` to bypass prefix validation.
3. This is a UX bug in the `beads` tool (`br`), since the user is told to use `--force` or `--rename-prefix` with `br doctor --repair`, but those arguments are not actually accepted by the `doctor` command.
4. Workaround: To repair the local DB in this workspace, one must manually drop the corrupt DB and sync from the JSONL source of truth using `rm .beads/beads.db && br sync --import-only --force`.

I have performed this manual workaround locally to fix the `.beads` database for this workspace. However, the root cause (unsupported flags in `br doctor --repair`) needs to be fixed upstream in the `beads` tool repository.
